  "doc_id": "29596",
  "text": "A cockroach has six legs, which support and move its body. It typically walks and runs in a tripod gait where the front and rear legs on one side of the body move in phase with the middle leg on the other side. The front legs swing head-high during normal walking so that many obstacles can be surmounted without a change in gait. However, when large barriers are encountered, the animal's gait changes and its contralateral legs move in phase. The cockroach also pitches its body up prior to climbing large obstacles and uses its body joints to avoid high centering during a climb [CITATION_1] . The cockroach turns by generating asymmetrical motor activity in legs on either side of its body as they extend during stance [CITATION_2] . These actions redirect ground reaction forces so as to alter the animal's heading [CITATION_3] .",
